fields.text:
I'm simultaneously me right now, but a child. I'm in elementary school. Alan Egli's there.  What I instantly know (because it's a dream and I have the backstory immediately) is that there's been some kind of major change to the world. We're in a dark, long winter that's been lasting a while. At the end of each day, the teachers tell us we're going to die. Not like "some day you'll freeze to death out there" - I mean we die at the end of the day. And we do every day. They give us a pill and we die, after school, every day.

I'm feeling mildly sad about death, conflicted about following the teachers' directions, and ultimately subversive about it. I can remember that we do this every day, but somehow we all still are acting like it's the end of our lives, like it's really sad. I start thinking about the logic of it. I look over to Alan, and he give me a quizzical look. I motion with my head the international sign for "come over here" and he does. Somehow we have a long and involved conversation in a very short amount of time - not that there's telepathy in my dream world, but because we're having similar thoughts. We can't really put our finger on it, so we're left standing looking at each other like there's something we're just not getting. I'm thinking over what we had said, and it clicks.

I lean over to him and whisper in your ear "You're not a very good spy." Without making a lot of fuss, I move to the front of the room, where everyone can see me. (We're in a wide hallway, near the front doors of the school - not unlike Calamus elementary, but it's dark and grey out no matter the hour, therefore it's kind of dark inside, even with the lights on.)  I position myself near the teacher - the way students do after class if they want to talk to the teacher next. I wait my turn, and then turn slightly, so I'm both talking to the teacher and addressing everyone else. I say in a loud voice "I just figured this out. We're not dying. We don't die now. If we did, every day, we couldn't be this old. We wouldn't remember yesterday. You're putting us to sleep till the morning."

The teacher is horrified I've broken the polite fiction that's existed for I-don't-know-how-long. Lots of kids don't get it, but Alan does. We get our winter gear on, and leave. Somehow we know that before the apocalyptic weather started, there were other buildings around. We hadn't been out of the elementary school for a long time. We struggled through the grey snow (volcanic ash does that) to some sort of other largish building. The doors are unlocked so we go inside.

It's another school. There's a group of children waiting in the hallway. As we walk through, I see my sister sitting with her class on benches. She looks up and says "The winter concert's tonight. I'm so nervous - I haven't seen Mom or Dad in a long time." She's hugely pregnant, and sitting with one knee up with her arm wrapped around it and her fingers to her mouth, chewing nails.

We leave. We leave knowing there will be more buildings with small groups of people. We know that there's probably a reason why everyone's kept apart, but we'd rather risk whatever we were being guarded from than be drugged again. The cold's not that bad, and we walk briskly through the empty streets.

My family went to visit the McNeils, to see Michelle and Shannon's kids. Anton, Alena and I had bought books for the kids. I was excited and nervous about them liking the books. Shannon and I discussed whether or not my boobs were too small for breastfeeding.

We went to a swimming pool. Anton was now a three-year-old, taking a series of swim tests. It was raining and cold, so he was wearing someone's navy blue acrylic sweater. When his name was called, he ran over to the pool, jumped in the shallow end, doggy-paddled to the deep end, took a deep breath, and sunk himself down to touch the bottom. When he cane up, he doggy-paddled over to the closest edge and got out. My mom was there, and she wanted to wrap Anton in a soaking wet navy blue towel. He refused. He was still wearing the oversized navy blue sweater.

I was in an Americorps-type group (I didn't recognize anyone on the team). We were sent to a country that resembled 60's-era Vietnam. We were to assist the American troops there. 

When we arrived, we discovered that the commander had gone off his rocker, and had used his power to intimidate his troops into carrying out his orders,  and opression tactics to subdue the locals.

We were shocked, of course, but as we talked to the soldiers, we learned of the commanders slow descent into madness, and his eventual takeover of everything. He was clever, so every solution we thought of was found to be faulty, for one reason or another, by the troops. They had already tried everything they could think of to try to unseat the commander, but they were deeply scared of him, so even though they all had weapons, they had never mutinied.

Every idea I came up with was met with an obstacle. I screamed as hard as I could in frustration, which shocked the troops. I think they had forgotton that the situation was as frustrating as it was, since they'd been a part of it for so long.

I finally came up with a plan to replace all the batteries in all the equipment (luckily everything used AA) with corroding, old batteries. Our band of Americorps and rogue soldiers had to think of every item that used a battery. This part was really satisfying. The tactic was that we'd be able to surrupticiously replace the batteries without detection, but they'd stop working soon after, with most items failing within a few hours of the others.

The plan worked, andsome of the walkie-talkies even exploded. The soldiers were snapped out of their complacency by the ituation, and the commander couldn't maintain control during the electrical outage.
The big question that didn't get answered was: can diamonds melt? If so, what do they turn into?

I was on the farm, alone. It was night, and there was a thunderstorm. The house was dark, except when there'd be a lightning flash. 

Someone came to the door - it was Aden Biehl. He said shit had gone down, and he had come here. While he put his stuff in a bedroom, I stood in the living room, looking out the big picture window. Lightning flashed, and I saw that there was a cow out. When Aden came back, I told him that there was a cow out, and he asked me if it was wearing anything. I thought back and realized it had been wearing a mackintosh  like the Gordon's Fish Sticks guy. 

Thoroughly spooked now, I went about locking all the doors. I went back to the picture window, where I saw a group of satyrs heading towards the house. They were laughing cruelly and looking like they wanted to make trouble. 

Something up the road caught one of their attention, and the pack headed towards Eldon's. One of the satyr was wearing checkered chef pants, and got the crotch stuck crossing the barbed wire fence. He howled as he struggled to free himself as his friends left him. He finally got free, and left. Relieved, I turned around to find that while I had been watching them, some of them had snuck up to the house and silently taken the door off the hinges and removed the hardware from the door, leaving us defenseless. I went down to the basement, sure that Grandpa Green would have had an extra door. My blood chilled when I saw the basement had been cleaned.

I was at a scientific research team outpost, where we were researching a giant sea animal that acted like a shark, but looked like a huge piranha.

Much like Jurassic Park, our director had built the research facility over the water as way to create sensational PR. We walked out the glass-fronted, half-submerged observation room onto a floating walkway.

Naturally, the team was always being attacked and eaten. I started doing some tests on the creatures, to find out what kind of predatory technique they used. I had a life-sized dummy on a flexible stick, and the creatures would leap over the walkway. They'd grab the dummy and go back into the water on the other side.

We began to learn about their behavior, and discovered that they were adapting their attacks. Just then, the creatures began to ram the glass-sided observation room from below. Leaks sprung up. Researchers became hysterical. I sloshed  my way around all the equipment to help people escape.

I, too, left the observation room, and ran to the mess hall to get help. No one there seemed to be panicked, so I ran to someone I thought would be able to take charge, but he wouldn't listen.

Next to him at the table sat a woman who overheard what I explained, and pulled out a piece of recycled, unlined paper and a box of crayons. She drew a child-like drawing of the creature flying over the floating walkway towards a stick figure, then said "Aha! I know!", and I understood this to mean that she had figured out not only why the creatures were attacking, but also how to stop them.
